Greenland on Thursday said it would cut its annual quota for its polar bear hunt as the animal was threatened by climate change.
More pregnant polar bears in Alaska are digging snow dens on land instead of sea ice, and researchers say climate warming is the likely cause.
Environmental activists, hunters and oil industry representatives spoke at a public hearing on whether the U.S. government should list polar bears as a threatened species.
On Dec. 27, Interior Secretary Dirk Kempthorne announced a proposal to list the polar bear as a threatened species under the Endangered Species Act because of the loss of its sea ice habitat from global warming.
Polar bears are the kings of the Arctic, having adapted to an environment where few predators can survive.
